  "text": "The properties of ParAK122R in NAC assembly and disassembly resemble those of wild-type ParA in the presence of ATP␥S (Fig. 5) [CITATION_1] . Both form NACs that are larger than those promoted by wild type ParA with ATP because the disassembly rate is dramatically reduced. These observations are consistent with the previous conclusion that ATP binding is necessary for NAC assembly and hydrolysis for disassembly [CITATION_2] . The defect with K122R further implicates ParB in complex disassembly. Because ParAK122R can hydrolyze ATP albeit less efficiently than wild-type, it seems likely that the basal ATPase activity of ParA is not sufficient for efficient complex disassembly. This in turn implies that NAC disassembly requires ParB stimulation of ParA ATPase activity.",
